answers.body_markdown:
`std::bit_cast` _copies_ the bits of its argument to a new value of a different type.

    float myFloat = 3.14;
    auto asUint = std::bit_cast&lt;uint32_t&gt;(myFloat);
    auto asBytes = std::bit_cast&lt;std::array&lt;char,4&gt;&gt;(myFloat);

`myFloat`, `asUint` and `asBytes` are separate variables with separate addresses. The compiler may be able to optimise some them away completely, but logically they are completely distinct values that just happen to have the same size and bits.

`std::start_lifetime_as` doesn&#39;t _do_ anything. It just informs the compiler that it can treat a range of memory as if it contained an array of the specified type. This then allows the developer use that memory without an array without triggering undefined behaviour. It doesn&#39;t modify physically modify the memory passed to it and it doesn&#39;t return anything. It&#39;s purely for C++ object model bookkeeping.

Since `answer` cannot be true if `while` loop is not broken, put the `answer` value check after `while` loop and break `for` loop if `answer` is true:  

    x &lt;- c(3, -7, 6, 3, 1, -7)
    n &lt;- length(x); n # = 6
    counter &lt;- 0
    answer &lt;- FALSE
    for (i in 1:(n-1)) {
        v &lt;- i + 1
        while (v &lt;= n) {
          counter &lt;- counter + 1
          if (x[i] == x[v]) {
            answer &lt;- TRUE
            break
          }
          else {
            v &lt;- v + 1
          }
           
        } #end while

        if(answer == TRUE)         
           break

